Physical Description Note#1: A large photograph album with green leather covers containing 55 albumen photographs, most labeled and numbered on the negative by Samuel Bourne. The photographs are titled in English in black ink on the album pages.
Abstract#1: An album of photographs of Northern India, almost all of which are taken by Samuel Bourne. The album itself was likely compiled later by a British colonial agent or traveler who selected these specific images from Bourne's many prints available for sale. Two prints of Mumbai at the start of the album have no photographer listed and a third image of an Indian carriage is labeled as Sheperd and Robertson. The majority of the photographs show monumental architecture, although a few images also focus on street scenes and daily life. Specific locations of photographs in this album include: the Agra area (21 photos), the Delhi area (12 photos), Varanasi (called Benares here; 5 photos), Mumbai, Govardhan, Lucknow, the Deeg Palace complex, and the Golden Temple in Amritsar.
Note#1: Reference: Ollman, A. Samuel Bourne: Images of India. c p. 6-20.
Note#2: Source: Ira Wolff Photographic History Collection

Title#1: Photograph album of Ho Chi Minh City compiled by Claude-Marie Devenet, circa 1895
Physical Description Note#1: Binding: bound in contemporary black cloth boards with marbled inner covers and flyleaves.
Abstract#1: A photograph album showing people and buildings in Ho Chi Minh City (then Saigon) and surrounding areas, at the time colonized by France and part of Indochina. It was likely compiled with a mix of studio photographs and original photographs by the French sculptor Claude-Marie Devenet in the 1890s. The images document French colonial city life, the surrounding rivers and river life, Vang Tau, native villages, and colonial French residencies, businesses, and people.
Note#1: Layout: typically one large photograph per page; occasional pages include 2 or more smaller photographs.
Note#2: Photographs: 95 albumen prints. A few of the photographs are numbered or labeled in the negative and eight are described in ink in French. Many of the photographs are city views of Ho Chi Minh City (Saigon), including the city harbor with the Customs House and headquarters of the Messageries Maritimes, port facilities, French navel ships and river steamers, native Vietnamese boats, the "dry dock workshops," the Grand Canal and Rue Charner, images in the Cholon area (Chinatown), the Governor's Palace, the "Banque de l'Indochine," "Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Coorporation," Mong Bridge, French monuments, French buildings and residences, Notre Dame of Saigon, and industrial facilities. Several photographs show the area around modern Vung Tau. Other photographs are unlabeled but show Vietnamese villages, boats, carts, rickshaws, rice fields, and families.
Note#3: Photographers: two of the photographs are conclusively tied to Emile Gsell, but it's likely others were taken by Gsell and other studio photographers in Saigon. Other images in the album appear to be originals, perhaps taken by Devenet or other French colonial agents in the late nineteenth century.
Note#4: The dates of photographs in the album span nearly three decades. The earliest dated photograph is 1870, a Gsell image of a group of Indigenous Vietnamese people. Other identifiable dates include Notre Dame of Saigon before and after completion (completed in 1880), the Governor's Palace (built in 1873) and the Mong Bridge (built in 1893-1894). Therefore, the album was likely compiled around 1895.
Note#5: The front cover includes the gilt-lettered name of the owner/compiler, "C.-M. Devenet," likely Claude-Marie Devenet, a French sculptor who lived from 1851-1931. Little is known about his life but it seems likely, based on this album, that he could have traveled to or had temporary residence in French colonial Saigon in the 1890s.
Subject Topic#3: Ho Chi Minh City (Vietnam)--Description and travel--Photographs

Title#1: Tonkin types : photograph album, between circa 1900 and 1909
Extent#1: 7 unnumbered leaves : 12 photographs ; album 9 x 14 cm, photographs 6 x 9 cm
Physical Description Note#1: Binding: red pebbled cloth wrappers with blind stamping and gilt lettering on the cover.
Abstract#1: A small, portable album with twelve mounted gelatin silver photographs of people and places in northern Vietnam captioned in French in the negative. The album was likely compiled and sold by the French photographer Pierre Dieulefils out of his studio in Hanoi, Vietnam during the first decade of the twentieth century for a French colonial audience.
Note#1: Pierre Dieulefils was a French photographer and postcard publisher based in French Indochina. In 1885 he arrived in Tonkin (northern Vietnam) as a soldier; in 1888 he established a photographic studio in Hanoi. Dieulefils published over 5,000 postcards, primarily of Indochina, between 1902 and the 1920s.
Note#2: Layout: album contains seven stiff leaves with photo windows, each with a mounted photograph.
Note#3: Photographs: the album inludes the following 12 photographs -- "Pecheurs" (five fishermen, four of whom are standing in a river with fising implements) -- "Bac Ninh citadelle" (the Bac Ninh citadel, occupied by French troops beginning in 1884) -- "Femme du delta" (one seated woman with a posed background) -- "Femme du delta" (also labeled Femme Tonkinoise, No. 424; one seated woman with a posed background) -- "Chanteuses" (a group of seven women in traditional Vietnamese dresses and headgear, as well as two men, one with a dan day) -- " ... en famille" (title cut off, a Vietnamese family with three adults and two children) -- "Pousse Pousse" (two men operating a rickshaw with another Vietnamese man inside) -- "Haiphong embarcadere" (Cam River in Haiphong, with a traditional Vietnamese boat in the foreground and large, French buildings and steamships in the background) -- "Fabricant de gongs" (gong makers, two men and two children) -- "Chasseurs" (two male hunters with dead birds) -- "Porteuse d'eau Muong" (a Muong water carrier) -- "Mandarin" (one seated Chinese man in a studio).
Note#4: Photographer: while none of the photographs are signed and the photographer's name does not appear on the album, at least one of these photographs is definitively taken by Pierre Dieulefils ("Porteuse d'eau Muong"). Based on the subject-matter (northern Vietnam), time period, language, and style, it seems quite likely the whole album was compiled and sold by Dieulefils.
Note#6: Date range is based on the prints and style of the album, although many of the photographs may have been taken earlier. One image was also published in Dieulefils' 1909 book.

Title#1: Photograph album of Japan, China, and the Pacific, 1900
Physical Description Note#1: A photograph album with floral decorated cloth covers containing 230 photographs (mostly gelatin silver but a few albumen prints). Most photographs are labeled in English.
Abstract#1: An album compiled with photographs from ship tours of Japan, China, and other locations in the Pacific Ocean. It is likely a group album, since it highlights multiple people, routes, and destinations. The majority of the photographs do not have a photographer listed, but a handful are labeled as taken by Mrs. Gillette, Mr. Lowe, or Dr. D. W. Anderson. While the photographs are not in much order, the most likely itinerary is that the group or main photographer left Vancouver, Canada on the RMS Empress of India ship, taking it to Hong Kong. They then spent time in China and Japan before taking the SS Doric ship back to San Francisco, arriving in the United States in April of 1900. Locations in Japan include Tokyo, Yokohama, Miyanoshita Onsen, Sugita, Kobe, Nara, and Kyoto. Locations in China include Hong Kong, Macao, Kowloon, Shanghai, and Canton. Many of the photographs are taken on the RMS Empress of India or the SS Doric ships at sea and include many western people labeled with last names or initials, making it difficult to positively identify anyone. A small number of other images show Manilla in the Philippines, Honolulu in Hawaii, and India.
Note#1: Source: Ira Wolff Photographic History Collection

Title#1: Photograph album of the Himalaya Mountains in India, 1863-1866
Physical Description Note#1: A large photograph album with green leather covers containing 29 albumen photographs, each labeled and numbered on the negative by Samuel Bourne. The photographs are titled in English in black ink on the album pages.
Abstract#1: An album of photographs taken by Samuel Bourne in the Indian Himalaya Mountains. The images in the album are a mix of images from the three Himalayan trips that Bourne made in 1863, 1864, and 1866. Title#1: Photograph album of East Malaysia and Shanghai, China by Clement Charles Newson, 1908-1912
Abstract#1: A photograph album by Clement Charles Newson of East Malaysia and Shanghai, China. The images in Malaysia include many in Sandakan and the Sabah state (then British North Borneo), as well as others from the upper Rajang River in the Sarawak state. Title#1: Photograph album of southern Vietnam and Ho Chi Minh City, circa 1890-1900
Abstract#1: Layout: typically one or two photographs per page, although the back of the album includes a few pages with three or four smaller images.
Abstract#2: Photographs: 76 albumen and gelatin silver photographs likely taken by a French colonial agent living in colonial Saigon (now Ho Chi Minh City) or a surrounding area; most include handwritten captions in French. Photographs show a variety of people and places in southern Vietnam including in Saigon, Tan An, Tra Vinh, Can Tho, Bac Lieu, Soc Trang, and Ca Bei. Multiple photographs show Angkor Wat in Cambodia. Two photographs show Lao warriors and one is of a Lao village. Some of the scenes do not have a location labeled but are likely from southern Vietnam, including a river regatta, public festivities, furniture factory workers, French colonial residents, and colonial buildings.
Abstract#3: A photograph album containing images from the late nineteenth century of southern Vietnam (then Cochinchina) and Ho Chi Minh City (then Saigon), as well as a few from Cambodia (Angkor Wat) and Laos. The album was likely compiled, and possibly photographed by, a French colonial agent in southern Vietnam, probably the family pictured in multiple images near the back of the album.
Note#1: A date in the 1890s is an estimate of when the album was compiled, based on a mix of albumen and gelatin silver prints. Some of the photographs may be from professional studios in the area and taken earlier.
Note#2: Binding: a black cloth binding stamped on the inside S. Ogawa, Photographer, Yokohama. It seems likely this was only a stamp for who sold the blank album, not who took or sold any of the photographs.

Title#1: Souvenir photograph album of Japan with photographs by T. Enami, Reiji Esaki, and others, between 1892 and 1899
Abstract#1: A souvenir photograph album of people and places in Japan, characteristic of albums popular with tourists in the late 1800s. They were often created at a photo studio or photo dealer using studio images (as opposed to a tourist's personal images). This album also includes two smaller-format snapshots of two western men posing with Japanese women on the first page who were likely the owners of the album. Almost half the images depict Japanese people (mostly women), while the others show a variety of views around Tokyo, Nikko, Kamakura, Matsushima, Mount Fuji, and unlabled locations.
Note#1: Layout: typically one large photograph per page. Not all the pages are filled.
Note#2: Photographs: albumen prints of Japan, particularly around Tokyo but also in Nikko, Kamakura, Matsushima, and Mount Fuji. About half of the photographs are of people, mostly portraits of Japanese women.
Note#3: Photographers: overall, the album seems to be a compilation of Japanese studio photographers. Nearly half of the photographs are labeled in the negative in English, but most are from an unknown studio that used a letter and number system (see Bennett, p. 157-160). Two are from the studio of T. Enami (823 Jinkyo (Red Bridge) Nikko and 834 The Sweet Flags Horikiri Tokyo) and at least two others are very likely photographed by Esaki Reiji (455 Lotus Pound [sic for Pond] Kamakura and B94 Matsushima, Inland Sea (Three Views in Japan) Part 1). While the other half of the images are unlabeled, they also appear to be from Japanese studios of the late 19th century.
Note#4: Date range: the two photographs numbered 823 and 834 from T. Enami likely date between 1892 (when his studio opened) and 1899, giving a likely date range for the album itself. Overall, the album is characteristic of souvenir albums from Japan in the late 19th century.
Note#5: Binding: wooden boards with an ornate lacquer design on the front cover depicting two women with Mount Fuji in the background; the women's faces and hands are done in porcelain relief. The album pages are bound in accordion style.

Title#1: Photograph album of Vietnam and Cambodia, approximately 1897
Extent#1: 1 volume : 66 photographs ; 27 x 36 cm + 6 mounted photographs
Physical Description Note#1: Binding: brown quarter sheep album with marble papered boards and marbled endpapers.
Abstract#1: A photograph album by a French traveler or colonial agent of Vietnam and Cambodia (then French Indochina) in the 1890s. The photographer traveled to the ruins of Angkor Wat, Angkor Thom, and Phnom Penh in Cambodia. They also traveled among indigenous people and villages in Southern and Central Vietnam. They seem to have been based in Ho Chi Minh City (then Saigon) and were part of an early bicycling club there called the "Groupe du Cercle Cycliste Saigon."
Note#1: Layout: a mix of large format photographs with one per page, other photographs arranged two per page, and some smaller photographs arranged four per page.
Note#2: Photographs: the album does not appear to be in much order, either thematic or chronologically. It appears to be largely photographs by the compiler, but a few come from studios and are labeled in the negative. It opens with a few photographs of Angkor Wat (two attributed to the photographer Émile Gsell) and a couple of Phnom Penh, Cambodia (a botanical garden and a domesticated elephant). It then includes some photographs of Ho Chi Minh City (then Saigon), including of ships in the harbor and a photograph of a Chinese firefighting crew. A few photographs throughout the album show a "Groupe du Cercle Cycliste Saigon," a group of French men with bicycles that who were part of an early bicycle club in colonial Saigon. The middle of the album includes six images from the arrival from or return to France, including two of the Suez Canal, two of Colombo (Sri Lanka) and two of Singapore. A next set of smaller images document a trip to the Central Vietnam Highlands, including photographs of indigenous groups such as the Cham, Mai (Ma), and some termed Moi (an umbrella term for Montagnards). Places visited by the photographer include: Nha Trang, Khanh-Hoa, Rach Gia, and Binh Thuan, as well as some locations that are difficult to find the modern equivalent (such as Ya Lam and Tan Linh). The album ends with many images of Angkor ruins, particularly those of Angkor Wat and Angkor Thom. There are also six loose, mounted photographs tucked into the album, but they are all duplicates of images also found in the album. These photographs were perhaps displayed separately at one time.
Note#3: Photographer: the photographer is never named or identified in the album. They were likely a French traveler or colonial agent in French Indochina. They seem to have traveled fairly extensively from Ho Chi Minh City (then Saigon) to Phnom Penh and Angkor ruins in Cambodia as well as a variety of locations in Southern and Central Vietnam. The album also includes a couple images from their arrival or return trip through the Suez Canal, Sri Lanka, and Singapore.
Note#4: Date: only one of the images is dated, the inauguration of the velodrome in Saigon, Oct. 2, 1897. It seems likely that the rest of the original photographs were taken in 1897 or the years just around that, and that the album was compiled in the late 1890s. A few of the studio photographs, particularly those of Émile Gsell, may have been taken as early as the 1860s, but his prints were sold out of photo studios for decades.

Title#1: Indochine Française : les races. Album no. 1
Abstract#1: A photograph album with 21 gelatin silver prints made by the French colonial government in Indochina showing people across many ethnic groups in modern-day Vietnam, Laos, and Cambodia. These handmade photo albums were made between 1924 and 1928 and often given to diplomats and prestigious visitors. "At least 7 different publications in the series are known. Since these albums were handmade or hand-assembled, there are numerous variants in terms of the wrappers, string ties, calligraphic text, and even possibly the photographs used for the front covers" -- bookseller.
Table of Contents#1: [On cover: woman from northern Vietnam] -- Hanoï - Juenes filles Tonkinoises -- Hanoï - Paysannes des environs -- Hanoï - Femme Tonkinoise avec son bébé -- Hué - Chez un mandarin de la coux d'Annam -- Hué - Les mandarins de la Cour d'Annam -- Thu-Dâù Mot - Types de Stiengs -- Types de Stiengs -- Darlae - Femmes Radé -- Haut Donaï - Femme Moï avec son bébé -- Haut Donaï - Type de Moï -- Bassae - Homme et femme Kha -- Tran Ninh - Femmes Phou thai Dam -- Luang Prabang - Jéune fille laotienne de la classe aristocratique -- Luang Prabang - Femme laotienne en costume de mariée -- Luang Prabang - Jeune femme laotienne -- Luang Prabang - S.M. Chao Sammathi -- Pnom Penh - Femmes et fillettes cambodgiennes -- Pnom Penh - Jeune femme cambodgienne -- Kandal - Jeune paysan cambodgien -- Pnom Penh - Danseuses du Roi

Title#1: Photograph album of Northern Vietnam and Hanoi, between 1888 and circa 1898
Physical Description Note#1: Binding: contemporary dark green half morocco with dark green pebbled cloth boards. Stiff pages attached through metal loops.
Abstract#1: A photograph album with images of French colonial North Vietnam (then called Tonkin and part of French Indochina) in the late nineteenth century. The owner of the album was very likely a French colonial agent or soldier, perhaps one of the French men pictured in the original images. The images are a mix of studio and original photographs of a variety of cities, towns, and people in Northern Vietnam.
Note#1: Photographs: 68 albumen, collodion silver printing-out paper, and silver gelatin prints of Northern Vietnam. About half of the images are studio photographs labeled and numbered in the negative and many of these seem to have come from the studio of Pierre Dieulefils, a French photographer based in Hanoi. The other half of the photographs seem to be originals taken by the owner or another amateur photographer and are unlabeled but appear to be in the Hanoi and Northern Vietnam region. The images generally depict a variety of cities, local peoples, and French colonists and colonial buildings. The labeled locations of the photographs include Hanoi in particular, but also Viet Tri, Haiphong, Lang Son, Do Son, Bat Bac, Bao Ha, Lao Cai, My Tho, Ban Thi, Song Da near Cho Bo, and Ha Long Bay. One photograph is labeled "Famille de Koat, chef pirate soumis." Unlabeled photographs show Angkor Wat, city streets, a variety of villages, boats, carts, a railway bridge, and water buffaloes.
Note#2: Date range is based on when Pierre Dieulefils opened his shop in Hanoi, since many of the studio photographs were likely purchased there. The album was probably compiled in the 1890s, since it is a mix of photographic types (albumen prints, collodion silver printing-out paper, and gelatin silver prints).

Title#1: Photograph album of a Japanese family in Manchuria, colonial Korea, and Japan
Alternative Title#1: Asia Bookroom's title: [Japanese family photograph album of Manchuria and colonial Korea]
Extent#1: 194 photographs in 1 album : black and white photographs ; album 19 x 29 cm, prints various sizes
Abstract#1: "A fascinating family album or collection of photographs compiled by a Japanese family who travelled in Manchuria and Korea in the years 1920-1922. Many of the photos are carefully labelled with place names, dates and personal names. There are photos of the South Manchurian Railway Company's Games in May, 1920 and several images of ceremonies at a South Manchurian Railway Company School near Dailan, as well as a photo of General Kawai Misao of the Kwantung Army, taken in 1921, and numerous photos taken in Gongzhuling, near Changchun, Piziwo now in Pikou Town, Pulandia District in Dalian. Other photographs show Yingkou, today a prefecture-level city in Liaoning Province, and a larger photograph (11 x 15 cm) an image of a park known at the time as West Park of Dalian or Tiger Park (as it had a tiger enclosure), but later renamed to: Central Park (1926), Lenin Park (1947), and finally in 1949 to Labour Park. Sixteen of the photos also show the effects of a large storm in August 1921. A few photos show the family in Japan, with shots of various landmarks in Kyoto."--Bookseller's description
Note#1: Most prints in album are described in hand-written captions on album leaves
Note#2: "194 black and white photographs most laid down in what appears to be a handmade Japanese family photograph album with captions in Japanese. Most photographs are 5.5 x 8 cm, some 8 x 10 cm and two 11 x 15 cm. The maroon card leaves of the album are friable, some are detached or beginning to detach, some are torn with loss or chipped at the lower edge. Twenty three photographs, which were probably laid down on missing last leaves of the album are loosely inserted. One of the loose photographs is torn in two. Some photographs show some mild fading, occasional spotting or browning. Sold as a very interesting collection of photographs."--Description from Asia Bookroom

Abstract#1: A photograph of a residence in Yangon (previously Rangoon), Myanmar (Burma). The image shows a large home with two Burmese workers dressed in all white clothing, while British individuals are taking their tea in front of the house, adorned in traditional western style clothes including one man in a top hat and the other two in pith helmets. Also seen in the photograph is a horse drawn carriage that fits under the porch of the residence. The title is written on the back of the photograph. It is possible that these individuals were also the ones who photographed the other images of Myanmar in this collection of 19 loose images.
Note#1: Collection origin: Ira Wolff Photographic History Collection
Note#2: This photograph is part of a set of 19 photographs of British colonial Burma (Myanmar), very likely taken by British colonists who lived in the area in the late 19th century. One of the photographs in the set is of a group of British people outside a large mansion, who may have been those taking the photographs.
